# AI Shortcuts

Keyword triggers that modify behavior when they appear at the start of a prompt. Shortcuts stack: `ULTRA AUDIT: app/services/employee.py` = deep reasoning + full code review.

## TDD Loop (Incubyte core discipline)

| Shortcut | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| `TDD: <behavior>` | Enter the full Red-Green-Refactor loop via `.cursor/skills/incubyte-tdd-loop/SKILL.md`. Write the smallest failing test first, commit with `test:`, then minimum impl, commit with `feat:`, then refactor. |
| `RED: <behavior>` | Write only the next failing test. Run it. Paste the failure. Commit with `test: ...`. Do NOT write production code. |
| `GREEN: <test>` | Given a failing test, write the minimum production code to pass it. Run all tests. Commit with `feat: ...`. |
| `REFACTOR: <target>` | Tests must already be green. Improve structure without changing behavior. Re-run all tests after every micro-step. Commit with `refactor: ...`. |

## Code Intelligence

| Shortcut | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| `AUDIT: <target>` | Full code review using `.cursor/agents/incubyte-code-reviewer.md` checklist. Read all modified/target files, run every checklist section (including TDD-discipline and craftsmanship), report issues by severity. |
| `TESTS: <target>` | Write tests following `incubyte-testing.mdc` TDD flow. Red-green-refactor. |
| `BUG: <description>` | Investigate root cause. Write a failing regression test first (RED), confirm it fails, then fix (GREEN). Update `tasks/lessons.md` if the bug reveals a non-obvious pattern. |
| `SEC: <target>` | Security audit per `incubyte-sql-safety.mdc`: scan for f-strings/`.format()` in SQL, missing input validation, secrets in code, broken auth. Report findings with severity. |

## Thinking Frameworks

| Shortcut | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| `ULTRA` | Maximum depth reasoning. Enumerate tradeoffs, edge cases, failure modes, and second-order effects before answering. Do not rush to a solution. |
| `STEP` | Step-by-step logical breakdown. Number every step. Show reasoning chain explicitly. |
| `WHY5` | Five Whys root cause analysis. Start from the symptom, ask "why?" five times, arrive at the root cause before proposing a fix. |
| `FIRST` | First principles reasoning. Strip all assumptions, identify the fundamental constraints, rebuild the solution from scratch. |
| `PRE` | Pre-mortem. Assume the proposed change fails in production. List the 5 most likely failure modes and how to prevent each. |
| `POST` | Post-mortem. Analyze what went wrong. Extract lessons and append to `tasks/lessons.md` using the standard format. |
| `INVERT` | Inversion. Define what failure looks like first, then derive the solution that avoids every failure path. |

## Output Formatting

| Shortcut | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| `TLDR` | 2-3 sentence summary only. No code, no detail. |
| `ELI5` | Explain using a simple analogy. No jargon, no technical terms. |
| `BLUF` | Bottom Line Up Front. State the conclusion/recommendation first, then provide supporting detail. |
| `SHORT` | Maximum 3 sentences. |
| `TABLE` | Present the answer as a comparison table with clear columns. |
| `DENSE` | Information-dense. No filler, no repetition. Assume expert audience. |

## Meta Control

| Shortcut | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| `DELPHI` | Three-pass loop: (1) generate a solution, (2) critique it — find weaknesses, edge cases, missed requirements, (3) produce an improved final version incorporating the critique. |
| `V2` | Take the previous output and produce an improved version. State what changed and why. |
| `ALT3` | Generate 3 distinct alternative approaches. For each: one-line summary, key tradeoff, and when to prefer it. |
| `SCOPE` | Before solving, define the problem boundary: what is in scope, what is out, what assumptions are being made, what unknowns remain. |

